{{Infobox diocese | jurisdiction = Apostolic Vicariate | name = Harar | latin = Vicariatus Apostolicus Hararensis | country = {{flag|Ethiopia}} | metropolitan = ''Immediately subject to the Holy See'' | rite = [[Latin Rite]] | cathedral = Pro-Cathedral of The Holy Name of Mary | cocathedral = | area_km2 = 260,000 | population = 6,453,000 | population_as_of = 2014 | catholics = 21,510 | catholics_percent= 0.3 | bishop = [[Angelo Pagano]], [[O.F.M. Cap.]] | coadjutor = | auxiliary_bishops= | map = File:Ethiopia - Vicariato apostolico di Harar.jpg }}
The '''Apostolic Vicariate of Harar''' ({{lang-la|Vicariatus Apostolicus Hararensis}}) is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[apostolic vicariate]] located in the city of [[Harar]] in Ethiopia.
The Vicariate Apostolic of Harar comprises East and West Hararghe zones and Fentale and Boset woredas of East Shewa in Oromiya Region; Harari Region Provisional Administration of Dire Dawa; Somali Region with exception of Afder and Liben Zones; Amibara worda of Afar Region
== History == * May 4, 1846: Established as the [[Apostolic Vicariate of Galla]] from the [[Apostolic Prefecture of Abyssinia]] * March 25, 1937: Renamed as Apostolic Vicariate of Harar
== Leadership == * Vicar Apostolics of Harar(Roman rite) ** Fr. [[Angelo Pagano]], [[O.F.M. Cap.]] (April 16, 2016 – Present) ** Bishop Woldetensaé Ghebreghiorghis, O.F.M. Cap. (December 21, 1992 – April 16, 2016) ** Fr. Woldetensaé Ghebreghiorghis, O.F.M. Cap. (later Bishop) (Apostolic Administrator 1987 – December 21, 1992) ** Fr. [[Georges Perron]], O.F.M. Cap. (later Bishop) (Apostolic Administrator 1982 – November 21, 1992) ** Bishop [[Urbain-Marie Person]], O.F.M. Cap. (July 3, 1955 – December 4, 1981) ** Fr. Urbain-Marie Person, O.F.M. Cap. (later Bishop) (Apostolic Administrator 1952 – July 3, 1955) ** Bishop [[Leone Giacomo Ossola]], O.F.M. Cap. (later Archbishop) (September 22, 1937 – October 19, 1943) ** Bishop [[André-Marie-Elie Jarosseau]], O.F.M. Cap. (April 6, 1900 – September 2, 1937) * Vicars Apostolic of Galla (Roman Rite) ** Bishop [[Louis-Taurin Cahagne]] (August 1880 – September 1, 1899) ** Bishop [[Guglielmo Massaia]], O.F.M.Cap. (later [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]]) (May 12, 1846 – August 1880)
