{{Infobox prepared food | name = Magiun of Topoloveni | image = | imagesize = | caption = | alternate_name = | country = [[Romania]] | region = [[Topoloveni]], [[Argeş County]] | creator = | type = [[Jam]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Plum]]s | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''Magiun of Topoloveni'''<ref>[http://www.cotidianul.ro/o-poveste-romaneasca-de-succes-magiunul-de-topoloveni-151899/ O poveste romaneasca de succes: magiunul de Topoloveni]</ref> is a traditional Romanian food based on [[plum]] which has received since 2011 a [[Protected Geographical Status]] from the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.economie.gouv.fr/directions_services/dgccrf/documentation/panorama/themes/signesqualite.htm|title=Accueil >> Documentation >> Panorama des textes|website=www2.economie.gouv.fr|language=fr}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Magiun of Topoloveni is a kind of [[jam]] made from very ripe fruit from various plum varieties without added sugar. It is from the town of [[Topoloveni]] in the [[Argeş County]].<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.maap.ro/pages/industrie_alimentara/caiet-de-sarcini-update-mai2010.pdf |title =''Caiet de sarcini - Magiun de prune Topoloveni'' |editor =Ministerul Agriculturii si Dezvoltarii Rurale |language =ro }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>
== History == The recipe of magiun of Topoloveni is attested since 1914.
The magiun of Topoloveni is produced exclusively in the area bounded by the municipalities of Boţarcani, Crinţeşti, [[Gorăneşti]], [[Inuri]], Goleştii Badii, Ţigăneşti, [[Topoloveni]] and Viţicheşti. This region, particularly suitable for growing plums, belongs to the [[Argeş County]] in the region of Wallachia. The pruneraies cover about 17,000 hectares.<ref>{{Cite web|url =http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:C:2010:241:0003:0007:FR:PDF |title= Règlement (CE) n° 510/2006 du Conseil " Magium de prune Topoloveni " n° CE : RO-PGI-0005-0763-04.03.2009 |editor =Journal officiel de l’Union européenne C 241/3 du 08-09-2010|language=fr}}.</ref>
The magiun became the first Romanian certified natural product and protected by European Union by order No. 338/2011 dated April 7, 2011 the European Commission has recognized a protected designation of origin and protected geographical indication in Magiun of Topoloveni.
In 2003, Romania has deployed troops in [[Afghanistan]], as a member of [[NATO]]. In 2009, 100% natural magiun of Topoloveni replaces marmalade in all [[NATO]] bases. In 2010, the factory of Topoloveni was appointed official supplier to the Romanian Royal House.<ref>[http://www.rri.ro/arh-art.shtml?lang=6&sec=397&art=24429 Le magiun dans l'OTAN] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120913164501/http://www.rri.ro/arh-art.shtml?lang=6&sec=397&art=24429 |date=2012-09-13 }}</ref>
== Etymology == The word ''magiun'' come from Turkish language ''macun'' which means "[[Spread (food)|spread]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dexonline.ro/definitie/magiun|title=Magiun|website=www.dexonline.ro|language=ro}}</ref>
== Preparation == For the recipe of magiun of Topoloveni, have to four different types of plums, then cooked for 10 hours without sugar, with very low heat until the magiun sticks to the spoon. The magiun of Topoloveni is a thick paste and homogeneous, dark brown, with dry matter content is a minimum of 55%. This concentration, which corresponds to 55° [[Brix]], ensures the preservation of the product, at a temperature of 20° Celsius maximum, without the addition of any additives.
Plums used for the production of magiun of Topoloveni belong to various local varieties of [[Prunus domestica]] : Boambe of Leordeni, Bistriteana, Brumarii, Centenar, Dimbovita, Grasa ameliorata, Grasa Romanesca, Pescarus, Pitestean, Silvia, Stanley, Tomnatici Caran Sebes, Tuleu fat, Tuleu timpuriu, Valcean, Vinata Romaneasca.
