{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}} {{Use British English|date=December 2013}} {{Infobox cave | name =Poca Roca Cave | other_name = | photo = 1782 Poca Roca rev Cooper Willyams.jpg | photo_width = | photo_caption = Poca Roca by Rev. [[Cooper Willyams]] in 1782 | map = | map_width = | map_caption = Map showing location of Middle Hill in [[Gibraltar]]. --> | map_alt = | location = under the Middle Hill of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]] | coords = | lat_d = | long_d = | coords_ref = | land_registry_number = | grid_ref_UK = | grid_ref_Ireland = | grid_ref = | depth = | length = | height_variation = | elevation = | discovery = | geology = [[Limestone]] | entrance_count = 1 | entrance_list = | difficulty = | hazards = | access = | show_cave = | show_cave_length = | lighting = | visitors = | features = | survey = | survey_format = | website = }} '''Poca Roca Cave''' is a cave in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]]. It is below [[Middle Hill, Gibraltar|Middle Hill]].<ref name=latesiege/>
==Geography== Gibraltar is sometimes referred to as the "Hill of Caves" and the geological formation of all the caves is limestone. The Poca Roca Cave fissure runs through the [[Rock of Gibraltar]] in a general west-east direction all the way from [[Bell Lane, Gibraltar|Bell Lane]] in the old town area to [[Catalan Bay]] on the coast.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Warren|first=Charles|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/article_S0016756800161898| accessdate=15 August 2013| title=Proceedings| doi=10.1017/S0016756800161898|authorlink=Charles Warren}}</ref>
==History== During the three-and-a-half-year-long [[Great Siege of Gibraltar]] the population of the Rock made use of the caves to shelter from the bombardment. [[Beefsteak Cave]] was used by Gibraltarians whilst Poca Roca cave was prepared for use by the [[Governor of Gibraltar]].<ref name=latesiege/> This cave was later used as a storage area for gunpowder after the siege had been abandoned in 1783.<ref name=latesiege>{{cite book|last=Drinkwater|first=John|title=History of the Late Siege of Gibraltar|year=1786|publisher=Spillbury|location=London|page=356|url=http://www.dotcom.gi/siege/chapter02.htm|chapter=2|quote=previous to the bombardment, for the Governor's reception ; but was afterwards converted into a powder magazine, being very convenient for the batteries on the heights.}}</ref> Nearby batteries are [[Green's Lodge Battery]] and [[Middle Hill Battery]].
In the 1860s, Captain Fred Brome, the governor of Gibraltar's prison, sought permission from the [[Governor of Gibraltar]] to explore [[Martin's Cave]], as well as [[St. Michael's Cave]], [[Fig Tree Cave]] and this cave, with the objective of finding archaeological evidence of the past use of the caves. The Governor agreed and a ten-member team of prisoners began the explorations. Martin's Cave was the first to be explored.<ref name="Transactions">{{cite book|author=International Congress of Prehistoric Archaeology|publisher=Longmans, Green, and co.|title=Transactions of the third session which opened at Norwich on the 20th August and closed in London on the 28th August 1868|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-RoAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA113|accessdate=3 January 2013|year=1869|pages=113, 134, 136-}}</ref>
